      # --- Load tourist locations ---
      tourist_df = pd.read_csv("FTV_Locations_Coordinates.csv")

      center_lat = tourist_df["Latitude"].mean()
      center_lon = tourist_df["Longitude"].mean()
      m = folium.Map(location=[center_lat, center_lon], zoom_start=8, tiles="cartodbpositron")
      # --- Add district boundaries (bold) ---
      folium.GeoJson(
          kerala_districts,
          name="Kerala Districts",
          style_function=lambda x: {
              "fillColor": "lightgreen",

              "fillOpacity": 0.2,
          },
          tooltip=folium.GeoJsonTooltip(

              sticky=True
          )

      # --- Add tourist locations ---
      max_vis = tourist_df["Visitors"].max()
      for _, r in tourist_df.iterrows():
          radius = max(5, (r["Visitors"] / max_vis) * 15)  # scale by Visitors
          popup_html = f"<b>{r['Location']}</b><br>Visitors: {r['Visitors']}"
          folium.CircleMarker(
              location=[r["Latitude"], r["Longitude"]],
              radius=radius,
              color="red",
              fill=True,
              fill_opacity=0.85,
              popup=folium.Popup(popup_html, max_width=250),
              tooltip=r["Location"]
          ).add_to(m)
      # --- Add toggle control ---
      folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)
      # Save interactive map
      m.save("kerala_tourist_districts_map.html")

      import pandas as pd
      import numpy as np
      import geopandas as gpd
      import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
      import matplotlib.patheffects as pe
      # -------- 0) Robust column detection (no remapping/loading again) ----------
      # Find the right column names even if casing/spaces differ
      def find_col(df, targets):
          targets = [t.lower() for t in targets]
          for c in df.columns:
              if str(c).strip().lower() in targets:
                  return c
          raise KeyError(f"None of {targets} found in columns: {df.columns.tolist()}")
      cat_col = find_col(tourist_gdf, ["category"])
      name_col = find_col(tourist_gdf, ["locations", "location", "name", "place"])
      # Drop any rows with bad geometries / NaN coords
      tourist_gdf = tourist_gdf.dropna(subset=["geometry"]).copy()
      tourist_gdf = tourist_gdf[
          np.isfinite(tourist_gdf.geometry.x) & np.isfinite(tourist_gdf.geometry.y)
      ].copy()
      # -------- 1) Project to Web Mercator (stable plotting + arrows) -----------
      kerala_3857 = kerala_districts.to_crs(3857)
      tourist_3857 = tourist_gdf.to_crs(3857)
      # -------- 2) Normalize categories to match your style map -----------------
      def norm_cat(s):
          s = str(s).strip().lower()
          s = s.replace("backwater", "backwaters")
          s = s.replace("hill station", "hill stations")
          s = s.replace("waterfalls", "waterfall")
          return s
      tourist_3857["_cat"] = tourist_3857[cat_col].map(norm_cat)
      # Your exact visual spec (hex colors ensure no name issues)
      style_map = {
          "city":           ("s", "#FFA500"),  # orange square
          "village":        ("s", "#FFC0CB"),  # pink square
          "backwaters":     ("o", "#006400"),  # dark green circle
          "hill stations":  ("^", "#FFD700"),  # yellow triangle
          "religious":      ("D", "#8B4513"),  # brown diamond
          "beach town":     ("o", "#00008B"),  # dark blue circle
          "waterfall":      ("D", "#FF0000"),  # red diamond
      }
      # -------- 3) Plot ---------------------------------------------------------
      fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 12))
      # District polygons
      kerala_3857.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor="black", facecolor="#CDEAC0", linewidth=0.7)
      # Bold district names with white halo (readable on any fill)
      for _, r in kerala_3857.iterrows():
          c = r.geometry.centroid
          ax.text(
              c.x, c.y, r["District"],
              ha="center", va="center", fontsize=0, fontweight="bold", color="black",
              path_effects=[pe.withStroke(linewidth=2.5, foreground="white")]
          )
      # Points by category (skip empty)
      for cat_key, (marker, color) in style_map.items():
          sub = tourist_3857[tourist_3857["_cat"] == cat_key]
          if sub.empty:
              continue
          sub.plot(ax=ax, marker=marker, color=color, markersize=70, alpha=0.95, label=cat_key.title())
      # Name labels with small offset + arrows (kept near the points, not thrown off-canvas)
      for _, r in tourist_3857.iterrows():
          x, y = r.geometry.x, r.geometry.y

      # -------- Load Tourist Data --------
      tourist_df = pd.read_csv("Top Category of Tourist Locations.csv")
      # Convert to GeoDataFrame
      tourist_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(
          tourist_df,
          geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(tourist_df["Longitude"], tourist_df["Latitude"]),
          crs="EPSG:4326"
      )
      # -------- Plot Map --------
      fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 12))
      # Plot Kerala district boundaries
      kerala_districts.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor="black", facecolor="#E0F2E9", linewidth=0.7)
      # -------- Normalize categories --------
      def norm_cat(s):
          s = str(s).strip().lower()
          if s in ["backwater", "backwaters"]:
              return "backwaters"
          if s in ["hill station", "hill stations"]:
              return "hill stations"
          if s in ["waterfall", "waterfalls"]:
              return "waterfall"
          if s in ["historical site", "historical_sites", "historical"]:
              return "historical_site"
          return s
      tourist_gdf["_cat"] = tourist_gdf["Category"].map(norm_cat)
      # -------- Category color map --------

          "historical_site": "#000000",   # black
      }
      # Collect texts for adjustText
      texts = []
      # Plot Tourist Locations + Labels
      for cat, color in style_map.items():
          subset = tourist_gdf[tourist_gdf["_cat"] == cat]
          subset.plot(ax=ax, markersize=50, color=color, label=cat, alpha=0.9)
          for idx, row in subset.iterrows():
              texts.append(
                  ax.text(

                      fontsize=7, fontweight="bold", color="black"
                  )
